    <section class="hero">
      <div class="hero-body">
        <h1 class="hero-title">Lion's Mane</h1>
        <p class="hero-eyebrow">The Focus Mushroom</p>
        <p>Lion's Mane (<em>Hericium erinaceus</em>) has been used in traditional Chinese and Japanese practices for centuries, valued for its ability to support focus and mental clarity. It was often consumed as a tea, including by monks during long periods of meditation.</p>
        <p>Today, it's one of the most widely studied functional mushrooms for cognitive performance, connecting centuries of use with modern research on brain health.</p>
      </div>
      <img class="hero-image" src="{{ 'lions-mane-hero.png' | asset_url }}" alt="Lion's Mane mushroom close-up" width="1664" height="1034" loading="lazy" />
    </section>

    <section class="mechanism">
      <h2>How Lion's Mane Works</h2>
      <p class="mechanism-intro">Lion's Mane is the most studied nootropic mushroom for cognition. Four mechanisms explain how.</p>
      <div class="mechanism-card">
        <div class="mechanism-points">
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">1.</span>Supports Nerve Growth Factor (NGF).</h4><p>Lion's Mane is one of the few natural compounds known to support the body's production of Nerve Growth Factor, the protein your brain uses to keep neurons growing, connected, and healthy. Its active compounds, hericenones and erinacines, have been studied for this effect for decades.</p></div>
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">2.</span>Promotes neurogenesis and neural plasticity.</h4><p>Lion's Mane plays a role in the formation of new neurons and the connections between them. Together, these are the biological foundation of how your brain learns, adapts, and stores memory.</p></div>
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">3.</span>Helps combat oxidative stress.</h4><p>The fruiting body contains antioxidant compounds that help neutralize the kind of daily free-radical damage that accumulates in nerve cells and contributes to cognitive aging.</p></div>
          <div class="point"><h4><span class="point-num">4.</span>Nourishes the gut-brain axis.</h4><p>Lion's Mane acts as a prebiotic for beneficial gut bacteria, which produce neurotransmitters and short-chain fatty acids that influence mood and cognition. What's good for your gut is often good for your brain.</p></div>
